{
  "texts": [
    "In this paper, we study the problem of nonlinear programming using the gradient descent method.",
    "The results were obtained by the authors by compiling and debugging the program text in C++.",
    "It should be noted that this work, like the previously presented works [5][6][7][8], can be considered as a test for novice researchers.Let's consider a nonlinear programming problem without restrictions.",
    "It is necessary to minimize the function:.𝑓(𝑥 1, 𝑥 2) = 𝑒 𝑥 1 2 +𝑥 2 2 + 4𝑥 1 -5𝑥 2,(1)Partial derivatives with respect to independent variables 𝑥 1, 𝑥 2 have the form:𝜕 𝑓(𝑥 1, 𝑥 2) 𝜕𝑥 1 = 𝑒 𝑥 1 2 +𝑥 2 2 2 𝑥 1 + 4,(2)𝜕 𝑓(𝑥 1, 𝑥 2)𝜕𝑥 2 = 𝑒 𝑥 1 2 +𝑥 2 2 2 𝑥 2 -5,(3)According to the gradient descent method [4], to minimize a function of n variables 𝑓(𝑥 1, 𝑥 2, … 𝑥 𝑛), to find the extremum, you need to construct a sequence of vectors {𝒙 (𝒌_ }, which must satisfy the condition:𝑓(𝒙 (0)) > 𝑓(𝒙 (1)) > …> 𝑓(𝒙 (𝑛)) (4).Sequence elements {𝒙 (𝒌) } are calculated by the formula:𝒙 (𝑘+1) = 𝒙 (𝑘) + 𝛼 𝑘 𝒑 (𝑘), 𝑘 = 0, 1, 2, …,(5)here 𝒑 (𝑘) -direction of descent, 𝛼 𝑘step length in this direction.The gradient of the function at some point 𝒙 (𝑘) is directed towards the fastest local increase in the function.",
    "Thus, it is necessary to descend in the direction opposite to the gradient, called the antigradient."
  ]
}